            {
                "heading": "The 430 Years Fulfilled (12:40-42)",
                "body": "The narrator inserts a precise chronological note: 'The time that the people of Israel lived in Egypt was 430 years. At the end of 430 years, on that very day (be-etsem ha-yom ha-zeh), all the hosts of the LORD went out from the land of Egypt.' The phrase be-etsem ha-yom ha-zeh ('on the bone/essence of this very day') emphasizes calendrical precision \u2014 YHWH operates on an exact timetable. The 430-year figure has generated debate. The LXX (the Septuagint \u2014 the ancient Greek translation of the Hebrew Bible, abbreviated LXX because tradition says 70 or 72 scholars produced it; see the Reader's Guide in Era 1) and the Samaritan Pentateuch (a separate textual tradition of the Torah preserved by the Samaritan community, sometimes agreeing with the LXX against the Masoretic Text) read 'the time that the people of Israel lived in Egypt and in the land of Canaan was 430 years,' including the patriarchal sojourns in the total. Paul's argument in Galatians 3:17 follows this tradition, counting 430 years from Abraham's call to Sinai. The Masoretic text, by contrast, locates the entire 430 years in Egypt. Either way, the theological point is the same: God's covenant clock ran to the precise moment of fulfillment. The designation of Israel as 'hosts of the LORD' (tsivot YHWH) uses military language \u2014 Israel departs not as a refugee column but as a marshaled army under divine command."
            },
